1
00:00:00,120 --> 00:00:02,580
- This is my honest advice for anyone

2
00:00:02,580 --> 00:00:04,380
who wants financial freedom,

3
00:00:04,380 --> 00:00:07,740
and it comes from years
of personal experience.

4
00:00:07,740 --> 00:00:11,760
You see, back in school, my
teacher saw me as a lost cause,

5
00:00:11,760 --> 00:00:13,920
which pushed me to drop out at 16

6
00:00:13,920 --> 00:00:16,260
and start an apprenticeship
as a carpenter,

7
00:00:16,260 --> 00:00:19,950
which involved making wooden
trash cans for only $2 an hour.

8
00:00:19,950 --> 00:00:22,890
This was just enough to cover my expenses.

9
00:00:22,890 --> 00:00:25,950
Every day felt the same
and blended into one.

10
00:00:25,950 --> 00:00:28,950
I was stuck on a hamster
wheel, never getting ahead.

11
00:00:28,950 --> 00:00:31,350
I knew if I didn't find a way to escape,

12
00:00:31,350 --> 00:00:34,020
then I'd end up just like
my soulless coworkers.

13
00:00:34,020 --> 00:00:35,370
I wanted to be free

14
00:00:35,370 --> 00:00:39,000
to do the things I loved without
being a slave to my boss.

15
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:40,530
So I came up with a plan

16
00:00:40,530 --> 00:00:42,720
and managed to achieve millionaire status

17
00:00:42,720 --> 00:00:45,180
and financial freedom within my 20s.

18
00:00:45,180 --> 00:00:47,430
A lot of people ask me,
is it still possible

19
00:00:47,430 --> 00:00:49,560
to become financially free today?

20
00:00:49,560 --> 00:00:52,470
And the answer is yes, absolutely,

21
00:00:52,470 --> 00:00:54,270
if you've got the right plan.

22
00:00:54,270 --> 00:00:57,060
So by the end of this
video, my goal is for you

23
00:00:57,060 --> 00:00:59,970
to have a clear roadmap
to get financially free

24
00:00:59,970 --> 00:01:01,620
as quickly as possible.

25
00:01:01,620 --> 00:01:02,490
Let's get into it.

26
00:01:02,490 --> 00:01:04,920
Step one is to find your freedom figure.

27
00:01:04,920 --> 00:01:07,050
Your freedom figure is the amount you need

28
00:01:07,050 --> 00:01:08,550
to live your life without having

29
00:01:08,550 --> 00:01:10,620
to worry about money ever again.

30
00:01:10,620 --> 00:01:12,210
Once it's invested correctly,

31
00:01:12,210 --> 00:01:14,370
it will generate enough passive income

32
00:01:14,370 --> 00:01:17,790
to fully support your lifestyle
without ever running out.

33
00:01:17,790 --> 00:01:19,890
I'll talk more about investing later on,

34
00:01:19,890 --> 00:01:23,220
but first, we need to nail down
what that figure is for you

35
00:01:23,220 --> 00:01:26,070
as this isn't a one size
fits all kind of thing,

36
00:01:26,070 --> 00:01:28,440
because financial freedom
means different things

37
00:01:28,440 --> 00:01:29,490
to different people.

38
00:01:29,490 --> 00:01:30,720
So the first thing you need

39
00:01:30,720 --> 00:01:33,900
to do is set your
financial freedom baseline.

40
00:01:33,900 --> 00:01:37,200
Maybe you want a life where
you go on vacation more often,

41
00:01:37,200 --> 00:01:41,310
drive a sports car, live in a
mansion, or buy a private jet.

42
00:01:41,310 --> 00:01:43,920
Just bear in mind the
fancier the lifestyle

43
00:01:43,920 --> 00:01:46,410
you are aiming for, the
tougher it'll be to get there.

44
00:01:46,410 --> 00:01:48,750
Personally, I've always valued the freedom

45
00:01:48,750 --> 00:01:50,100
that comes from not having

46
00:01:50,100 --> 00:01:52,950
to chase money over
living a lavish lifestyle.

47
00:01:52,950 --> 00:01:56,820
So I made a rule early on
to only increase the quality

48
00:01:56,820 --> 00:01:59,910
of my lifestyle slightly
each and every year.

49
00:01:59,910 --> 00:02:02,160
Let's go through the
different areas of your life

50
00:02:02,160 --> 00:02:05,730
and estimate what each one
might cost to live comfortably.

51
00:02:05,730 --> 00:02:07,740
I'll be basing this on studies that show

52
00:02:07,740 --> 00:02:10,440
what people in their
20s typically aspire to.

53
00:02:10,440 --> 00:02:12,450
Now, grab a piece of paper

54
00:02:12,450 --> 00:02:15,720
and feel free to adjust the
numbers to match your own goals.

55
00:02:15,720 --> 00:02:17,820
So first up, your house,

56
00:02:17,820 --> 00:02:20,130
for most people in their 20s, city life

57
00:02:20,130 --> 00:02:22,500
or a place on the outskirts is ideal.

58
00:02:22,500 --> 00:02:24,870
If you get a spot in
Miami, you could be paying

59
00:02:24,870 --> 00:02:28,890
around about $30,000 per year

60
00:02:28,890 --> 00:02:30,540
for a one bedroom flat,

61
00:02:30,540 --> 00:02:31,800
and if you're in the UK,

62
00:02:31,800 --> 00:02:34,020
then London's rent prices
are pretty similar.

63
00:02:34,020 --> 00:02:35,640
Next up is your car.

64
00:02:35,640 --> 00:02:37,620
Now the Porsche 911 always seems

65
00:02:37,620 --> 00:02:40,230
to appear on dream car list, so let's use

66
00:02:40,230 --> 00:02:41,760
that as an example.

67
00:02:41,760 --> 00:02:43,920
Luxury cars like this
come with higher costs

68
00:02:43,920 --> 00:02:45,930
after considering fuel, maintenance

69
00:02:45,930 --> 00:02:48,360
and insurance on top of the car payment,

70
00:02:48,360 --> 00:02:52,387
you'd be looking at a
total of around $24,125.

71
00:02:54,540 --> 00:02:58,140
Now for vacations, according
to the New York Post,

72
00:02:58,140 --> 00:03:00,180
Gen Zs are far more interested in

73
00:03:00,180 --> 00:03:02,670
traveling than my generation ever was.

74
00:03:02,670 --> 00:03:05,880
Back in my day, one
vacation felt extravagant,

75
00:03:05,880 --> 00:03:07,770
but now the sweet spot seems to be

76
00:03:07,770 --> 00:03:09,450
around three trips for a year.

77
00:03:09,450 --> 00:03:11,400
For three mid-range trips,

78
00:03:11,400 --> 00:03:14,463
you're looking at about $5,000,

79
00:03:15,660 --> 00:03:18,090
and of course, if you're
bringing someone along,

80
00:03:18,090 --> 00:03:19,560
you can expect to double that.

81
00:03:19,560 --> 00:03:22,950
Next, we have to consider
the boring bills.

82
00:03:22,950 --> 00:03:25,920
If we stick with the one
bedroom apartment in a city,

83
00:03:25,920 --> 00:03:28,230
then with electricity, heating, water

84
00:03:28,230 --> 00:03:29,820
and internet, I'd estimate

85
00:03:29,820 --> 00:03:33,900
that this would cost
about $3,000 per year.

86
00:03:33,900 --> 00:03:35,160
Next is food.

87
00:03:35,160 --> 00:03:37,170
Now, I'd assume you'd want a mix

88
00:03:37,170 --> 00:03:39,390
of home cooking and eating out.

89
00:03:39,390 --> 00:03:43,320
I reckon you could do this
for about $5,000 per year.

90
00:03:43,320 --> 00:03:45,330
Now for health insurance,

91
00:03:45,330 --> 00:03:47,550
this isn't really needed in the UK,

92
00:03:47,550 --> 00:03:49,830
but if you're in the
USA, then you can expect

93
00:03:49,830 --> 00:03:53,940
to pay 2,500 per year

94
00:03:53,940 --> 00:03:55,230
for a mid-level plan.

95
00:03:55,230 --> 00:03:57,570
Finally, there's leisure.

96
00:03:57,570 --> 00:04:00,300
This covers your gym
membership, nights out

97
00:04:00,300 --> 00:04:01,290
and any other spur

98
00:04:01,290 --> 00:04:04,140
of the moment spending, a
reasonable yearly budget

99
00:04:04,140 --> 00:04:07,560
for this would be around $4,000.

100
00:04:07,560 --> 00:04:09,900
Once you've written down
your cost for each category,

101
00:04:09,900 --> 00:04:11,820
add them up to see how much you'll need

102
00:04:11,820 --> 00:04:13,860
to live your dream life each year.

103
00:04:13,860 --> 00:04:16,143
In our example, that adds up to.

104
00:04:19,111 --> 00:04:19,944
Right.

105
00:04:19,944 --> 00:04:23,480
That's $75,325 a year.

106
00:04:25,680 --> 00:04:27,270
How's that for a bit of quick maths?

107
00:04:27,270 --> 00:04:30,900
Now, to find your freedom
figure, take that yearly number

108
00:04:30,900 --> 00:04:34,080
and multiply it by 25.

109
00:04:34,080 --> 00:04:35,340
We use 25

110
00:04:35,340 --> 00:04:39,390
because of a rule called
wait for it, the rule of 25.

111
00:04:39,390 --> 00:04:40,223
Who'd have guessed that?

112
00:04:40,223 --> 00:04:41,790
This rule is a way to figure out

113
00:04:41,790 --> 00:04:43,320
how much you'll need invested

114
00:04:43,320 --> 00:04:45,330
so that you can take money out each year

115
00:04:45,330 --> 00:04:47,040
without ever running out.

116
00:04:47,040 --> 00:04:50,910
In our example, 75,325

117
00:04:50,910 --> 00:04:55,910
multiplied by 25 gives us $1,883,125.

118
00:05:00,390 --> 00:05:02,640
Think of it like having a golden goose

119
00:05:02,640 --> 00:05:05,880
that lays just enough eggs
each year for you to live on.

120
00:05:05,880 --> 00:05:07,620
As long as you only take the eggs

121
00:05:07,620 --> 00:05:09,090
and don't eat the goose,

122
00:05:09,090 --> 00:05:11,880
it keeps producing more eggs every year.

123
00:05:11,880 --> 00:05:14,070
That way you can keep living off the eggs

124
00:05:14,070 --> 00:05:16,740
without ever using up
your main money stash.

125
00:05:16,740 --> 00:05:18,000
This is assuming you are able

126
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:20,760
to get more than a 4% return on your money

127
00:05:20,760 --> 00:05:24,150
and while past results aren't
a guarantee of future returns,

128
00:05:24,150 --> 00:05:26,820
the average annual return of the S&P 500

129
00:05:26,820 --> 00:05:30,660
over the last 10 years
has been around 12 to 14%,

130
00:05:30,660 --> 00:05:31,980
although this is slightly higher

131
00:05:31,980 --> 00:05:33,420
than the longer term average,

132
00:05:33,420 --> 00:05:36,030
no one has ever lost any
money if they have bought

133
00:05:36,030 --> 00:05:38,370
and held an S&P 500 index fund

134
00:05:38,370 --> 00:05:41,700
for more than 20 years based
on historical averages.

135
00:05:41,700 --> 00:05:44,520
So how do you invest in the S&P 500?

136
00:05:44,520 --> 00:05:48,300
Well just download an
investing app like Trading 212.

137
00:05:48,300 --> 00:05:51,990
Once you're in, search for an S&P 500 ETF,

138
00:05:51,990 --> 00:05:55,290
which lets you invest in
the top 500 US companies

139
00:05:55,290 --> 00:05:56,250
all at once.

140
00:05:56,250 --> 00:05:58,440
Trading 212 lets you invest in something

141
00:05:58,440 --> 00:05:59,910
called fractional shares.

142
00:05:59,910 --> 00:06:02,010
This is great as it means the stock market

143
00:06:02,010 --> 00:06:04,020
isn't just for the rich investors anymore

144
00:06:04,020 --> 00:06:06,300
and the average person can get involved.

145
00:06:06,300 --> 00:06:08,310
If you are just starting
out, it's a good idea

146
00:06:08,310 --> 00:06:11,070
to use a strategy called
dollar cost averaging.

147
00:06:11,070 --> 00:06:13,590
This basically means you're
investing the same amount

148
00:06:13,590 --> 00:06:17,400
on a consistent basis, whether
the market is up or down.

149
00:06:17,400 --> 00:06:19,110
The idea is that over time,

150
00:06:19,110 --> 00:06:21,420
this will help you average out your costs

151
00:06:21,420 --> 00:06:23,640
so that you don't buy
all in when the market

152
00:06:23,640 --> 00:06:25,140
is its most expensive.

153
00:06:25,140 --> 00:06:26,760
Rather than doing this manually,

154
00:06:26,760 --> 00:06:29,910
you can actually set up the
app to invest automatically

155
00:06:29,910 --> 00:06:33,480
for you on a regular basis
using the pies feature.

156
00:06:33,480 --> 00:06:36,600
Since I was planning to talk
about trading 212 anyway,

157
00:06:36,600 --> 00:06:38,880
I reached out to them to
see if they'd be interested

158
00:06:38,880 --> 00:06:41,310
in sponsoring this portion of the video.

159
00:06:41,310 --> 00:06:44,370
They agreed and are offering
a free fractional share worth

160
00:06:44,370 --> 00:06:46,500
up to a hundred pound to anyone

161
00:06:46,500 --> 00:06:49,050
that uses the code tilbury
when they create an account.

162
00:06:49,050 --> 00:06:52,410
Plus, you can get more free
shares by inviting your friends.

163
00:06:52,410 --> 00:06:54,300
Both of you will get a free share

164
00:06:54,300 --> 00:06:55,950
as long as they fund their account.

165
00:06:55,950 --> 00:06:58,470
I'll leave a link in the
description if you're interested.

166
00:06:58,470 --> 00:07:00,600
Step two is to hack your life.

167
00:07:00,600 --> 00:07:02,430
I get that reaching your freedom figure

168
00:07:02,430 --> 00:07:03,690
in an investment account

169
00:07:03,690 --> 00:07:05,940
might seem like an impossible task.

170
00:07:05,940 --> 00:07:09,000
It definitely felt that way
for me when I first started,

171
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:10,620
but there are a few strategies

172
00:07:10,620 --> 00:07:12,360
that can help you get there faster.

173
00:07:12,360 --> 00:07:15,660
I highly suggest taking a
closer look at all the areas

174
00:07:15,660 --> 00:07:18,330
where money might be slipping
through your fingers.

175
00:07:18,330 --> 00:07:21,630
Chances are you are spending
far more than you realize on

176
00:07:21,630 --> 00:07:23,460
things that don't really matter to you.

177
00:07:23,460 --> 00:07:25,920
Don't worry, I'm not gonna
lecture you about skipping

178
00:07:25,920 --> 00:07:28,470
Starbucks or making
packed lunches every day.

179
00:07:28,470 --> 00:07:31,290
I'm sure you've heard enough
of that advice from my Shorts.

180
00:07:31,290 --> 00:07:33,870
Instead, I wanna show you clever ways

181
00:07:33,870 --> 00:07:36,630
to keep living the life
you love while saving money

182
00:07:36,630 --> 00:07:38,250
through some smart hacks.

183
00:07:38,250 --> 00:07:40,200
Let's kick things off with car hacking

184
00:07:40,200 --> 00:07:43,020
because I think a lot of
people need to hear this.

185
00:07:43,020 --> 00:07:45,060
Social media might have you thinking

186
00:07:45,060 --> 00:07:48,780
that everyone is driving around
in Range Rovers and Lambos,

187
00:07:48,780 --> 00:07:52,080
but let me tell you, that's
usually not the case.

188
00:07:52,080 --> 00:07:54,270
Most of these people have
their cars on finance

189
00:07:54,270 --> 00:07:57,810
or loans paying hundreds
of dollars every month

190
00:07:57,810 --> 00:07:59,490
just to keep up appearances.

191
00:07:59,490 --> 00:08:02,910
According to LendingTree, the
average monthly car payment

192
00:08:02,910 --> 00:08:06,270
for a new vehicle in
2024 hit a whopping $734.

193
00:08:08,160 --> 00:08:11,640
That's almost $9,000
a year down the drain.

194
00:08:11,640 --> 00:08:14,190
The worst part, most
people can't even afford

195
00:08:14,190 --> 00:08:16,260
these payments, which is why there are

196
00:08:16,260 --> 00:08:18,210
around a hundred million Americans

197
00:08:18,210 --> 00:08:20,520
with outstanding car loans right now.

198
00:08:20,520 --> 00:08:22,770
So let me give you some advice.

199
00:08:22,770 --> 00:08:24,720
Don't get sucked into this trap.

200
00:08:24,720 --> 00:08:27,000
Just because your mates
are taking out car loans

201
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:31,020
doesn't mean you have to,
instead think about car hacking.

202
00:08:31,020 --> 00:08:33,360
This means buying a quality used car

203
00:08:33,360 --> 00:08:36,960
that's already hit the bottom
of its depreciation curve.

204
00:08:36,960 --> 00:08:38,730
You can drive it for a few years

205
00:08:38,730 --> 00:08:41,520
and then sell it for
close to what you paid.

206
00:08:41,520 --> 00:08:43,170
No massive monthly payments

207
00:08:43,170 --> 00:08:45,180
and no debt hanging over your head.

208
00:08:45,180 --> 00:08:47,550
Next up, let's talk about something I like

209
00:08:47,550 --> 00:08:49,290
to call brand hacking.

210
00:08:49,290 --> 00:08:51,210
This is all about picking generic

211
00:08:51,210 --> 00:08:54,240
or store brand products
over the big name brands

212
00:08:54,240 --> 00:08:57,810
to save a bit of cash without
losing out on quality.

213
00:08:57,810 --> 00:09:01,140
A study from moneysavingexpert.com
actually found

214
00:09:01,140 --> 00:09:04,200
that people can save up to 87% by going

215
00:09:04,200 --> 00:09:07,080
with generic versions
instead of the branded items.

216
00:09:07,080 --> 00:09:10,350
But let's get practical so
you can see what I mean.

217
00:09:10,350 --> 00:09:12,720
Here's a box of Cocoa Pops.

218
00:09:12,720 --> 00:09:13,980
Absolutely classic.

219
00:09:13,980 --> 00:09:17,760
Everyone loves them and I
always keep a box under my desk,

220
00:09:17,760 --> 00:09:21,810
but they cost around $4.25 for a box,

221
00:09:21,810 --> 00:09:25,830
and here's a box of Choco
Rice, the unbranded version,

222
00:09:25,830 --> 00:09:29,100
which costs around $1.66 a box.

223
00:09:29,100 --> 00:09:31,170
By choosing the unbranded cereal,

224
00:09:31,170 --> 00:09:34,080
you're saving $2.56 each time,

225
00:09:34,080 --> 00:09:36,360
and honestly, I bet most people couldn't

226
00:09:36,360 --> 00:09:37,860
even taste the difference.

227
00:09:37,860 --> 00:09:41,550
Plus you get 500 grams over the 290 grams

228
00:09:41,550 --> 00:09:44,970
in the branded box, so it's
gonna last nearly twice as long.

229
00:09:44,970 --> 00:09:46,117
I know what you're thinking.

230
00:09:46,117 --> 00:09:50,070
$2.56 isn't gonna make me
a millionaire anytime soon.

231
00:09:50,070 --> 00:09:54,570
Well, actually, if you
save $2.56 every day,

232
00:09:54,570 --> 00:09:57,930
that's $934.40 a year.

233
00:09:57,930 --> 00:09:59,400
Do that for five years

234
00:09:59,400 --> 00:10:03,540
and you've saved $4,672

235
00:10:03,540 --> 00:10:06,150
and that's just from one small swap.

236
00:10:06,150 --> 00:10:07,770
Think about how much you could save

237
00:10:07,770 --> 00:10:10,650
by making similar swaps in
other parts of your life.

238
00:10:10,650 --> 00:10:14,190
It's all about those small
adjustments, adding up over time

239
00:10:14,190 --> 00:10:16,080
and making your money go further.

240
00:10:16,080 --> 00:10:19,230
Now for the big one, house hacking,

241
00:10:19,230 --> 00:10:20,610
as we know from step one,

242
00:10:20,610 --> 00:10:23,010
housing is usually your biggest expense,

243
00:10:23,010 --> 00:10:24,840
but what if you could reduce

244
00:10:24,840 --> 00:10:27,780
or even completely eliminate that cost?

245
00:10:27,780 --> 00:10:30,450
You are probably expecting me
to say, live with your parents

246
00:10:30,450 --> 00:10:32,610
or go for a smaller apartment,

247
00:10:32,610 --> 00:10:35,610
and while those are good options,
they don't suit everyone.

248
00:10:35,610 --> 00:10:38,160
So here's a smarter strategy you can use.

249
00:10:38,160 --> 00:10:40,140
Instead of getting a typical apartment,

250
00:10:40,140 --> 00:10:41,580
think about getting a duplex

251
00:10:41,580 --> 00:10:43,800
or a property with an extra room or two.

252
00:10:43,800 --> 00:10:46,980
Sure, this might mean a
slightly higher deposit upfront,

253
00:10:46,980 --> 00:10:48,300
but it's worth it.

254
00:10:48,300 --> 00:10:49,560
You live in one unit

255
00:10:49,560 --> 00:10:52,290
and rent the other one out,
using this rental income

256
00:10:52,290 --> 00:10:55,590
to cover most if not all of your mortgage.

